description:
Flower market
on 28th Street between 6th and 7th Avenues.
Stores throughout the block. The stores all close by 6pm; regulars check early, but there are still flowers and plants for all until late at night. Now THATs romantic!!!
author: herbieGB

description:
Peanut Butter and Co.
3rd St. and Sullivan, below Washington Square Park.
Peanut butter and banana sandwiches, whole grain bread, celery and carrot sticks, cups of peanut butter.
author: herbieGB

description: The Freegan website calls this uptown Garden of Eden grocery store "one of the best diving sites in the city." They have a great deal of leftovers from the hot buffets and premade dinners in addition to the usual produce.
author: herbieGB

description:
Gourmet Garage. NOTE that this is in reference to when the store was on Broome and Mercer, so may no longer apply:

This is the flagship store, so when you can get at it, its a motherlode. Several giant dumpsters on the Mercer Street side. Rumor has it that these dumpsters are sometimes locked; it is more likely that security or a night manager will yell at you and/or chase you away. Go after 11pm.
author: herbieGB

description:
BabyCakes (248 Broome St)

You can find tasty cakes and sweets. BabyCakes offers all natural, organic and delicious alternatives free from the common allergens: wheat, gluten, dairy, casein and eggs. Their cakes don't contain white sugar or toxic chemical sweeteners. At Sunday around 18:00 they put out the cakes in back plastic bags right outside the door.
author: NA

description:
Au Bon Pain (6 Union Square E)

Plenty of bread in diverse forms like ciabatta, whole wheat multigrain bread and baguette can be found in big amounts. On Sunday around 17:00 they throw out bread and pastries left over from the weekend in big amounts which can last for the whole week. When you bring it home put it in the fridge and when you feel like having a sandwich simply put some water on the bread and put it in the oven. It comes out crispy and tasty.
author: NA

description: Associated Supermarket -- They throw out a lot of good produce, including bananas.
author: NA

description:
Gristede's (101 Clark St)

Clear garbage bags out front, best after 9:30pm. Routinely hit or miss, but the hits can be great: dozens of eggs, bags of chocolate chips, cheese.
author: NA

description:
Associated Supermarket (229 Knickerbocker Ave)

I was there in the late afternoon, and there were several bags out. I found cocunuts, yucca, grapes, carrots, garlic, and other types of produce.
author: Wendy

description:
Pom Distributor (Ash Street just west of Pulaski Bridge)

Continued existence and precise location needs verification. Look for Pom trucks inside parking lot. Dumpster is at the back of the lot. This is the legendary juice dumpster; one freegan.info edito stumbled upon it in June 2012. In the late afternoon of a weekday, the gate was open and the dumpster chock full of everything from pomegranate juice to lemonade to smoothies and lattes. Everything was acceptably cool; no bottles were bloated. Some were way past “pull date”.
author: NA

description:
Lowell Importers

Continued existence and precise location needs verification. Importer and distributor and Greenpoint Avenue and West Street, southwest corner. Best to visit the two dumpsters on Monday, Tuesday, and Thursday 9pm. Polish cheeses, farmer cheese, sliced sandwich cheese, spreads, yogurts.
author: NA

description:
Greens & Ackermans Bakery (65 Franklin Ave)

Two overstuffed dumpsters at Franklin between Park and Flushing. Cakes, cupcakes.
author: NA

description:
Sunac Natural Food (150 N 7th St)

Kind of a health food 7-11. Packaged salads, grapes, and other produce.
author: NA

description:
Sunac Natural Food (440 Union Ave)

Open 24 hours a day, so it's not for the shy. They put out a mountain of garbage bags every night except Saturday after about 9:30pm.  It's all right on the curb and there's ALWAYS something good. Bags of mushrooms, greens, packaged goods, and even food buckets are often found. Picked up before Midnight. Bring friends 'cause there's a lot!
author: NA

description:
Foodtown of Williamsburg (159 N 3rd St)

Lots of prepared foods, some produce. In November 2011 we also found lots of unopened beverages, including kambucha.
author: NA

description:
Duane Reade (250 Bedford Ave)

As of November 2011, lots of  fruit, vegetables, bread, packaged sandwiches, cooked meats and salads. Verifies what we’ve heard from locals and a contributor (Jan 2011).
author: NA

description:
The Bagel Store (349 Bedford Ave)

They toss bagels, somewhat erratically.
author: NA

description:
Khim’s Millenium Market (265 Bedford Ave)

At least we think the trash was from there. We found lots of produce and sandwiches, plus canned goods (including, weirdly, Hershey’s syrup).
author: NA

description:
Southside Food Plaza (428 Bedford Ave)

Kosher supermarket, lots of fruits, vegetables, and snacks.
author: NA

description:
Food Bazaar (21 Manhattan Ave)

Several large dumpsters in the east corner of the parking lot, the corner farthest away from the store itself. There are gates, but left open. Veggies, herbs, fruit, meats and cheeses, junk food and more. Needs more exploration, but on our midweek trailblaze food was out at 10pm.
author: NA

description:
Bravo Supermarket (4261 Broadway)

Good selection of produce, includes some Latin American specialty items.
author: NA

description: Mike's Bagels (4003 Broadway)
author: NA

description:
Morton Williams (2941 Broadway)

When I've gone the staff have been in the process of throwing stuff out, around 9 or 9:30pm, and they were friendly enough about letting us dive away. It's a very busy corner, and well-lit, so its high-profile dumpster diving, not for the shy.
author: NA

description:
D'Agostino (2828 Broadway)

I'm not sure what the best time is, but I think 9-9:30pm is when I've had good luck there.

Closed permanently in April 2016
author: NA

description:
Absolute Bagels (2788 Broadway)

The usual bagel abundance, plenty fresh.
author: NA

description:
Garden of Eden (2780 Broadway)

One of the best diving sites in the city. Super high end fresh produce in huge plastic barrels, bags of fresh-made packaged entrees, loose buffet bar food, lots more. Enormous volume. Lots of exotic produce. You'll find stuff there from 9:30 or 10pm on.
author: NA

description:
Silver Moon Bakery (2740 Broadway)

We found meat and cheese sandwiches as well as bread.
author: NA

description:
Hot & Crusty (2393 Broadway)

All the bready stuff - muffins, pizza slices, rolls, croissants, etc. We had more luck with the store in the 80s.
author: NA

description:
Gristede's (2700 Broadway)

Normal supermarket stuff, although we didn't find much produce. Lots of eggs and bread though.
author: NA

description:
Health Nuts (2611 Broadway)

We found mostly prepared foods, some vegetarian and vegan, some not.
author: NA

description:
Gary Null's Uptown Whole Foods (2421 Broadway)

Produce, pretty much. Food is out by 10:30 pm, perhaps earlier.
author: NA

description:
Barzini's (2451 Broadway)

Lots of good produce.
author: NA

description:
Zabar's and Company Inc (2245 Broadway)

Would seem like a sure bet, but we haven’t seen anything here yet. If anyone does, please update this info.
author: NA

description:
Fairway Market (2127 Broadway)

Would seem like a sure bet, but we haven’t seen anything here yet. If anyone does, please update this info.
author: NA

description:
Gracefully

On a first run (October 2012), we found cheese packs, individual drinks, hotdogs, sushi, packaged and unpackaged produce, and more. Worth further exploration.
author: NA

description:
Western Beef (75 West End Ave)

Dumpster is against the building on 62nd. On a first run (October 2012), plentiful packaged and unpackaged produce, some non-perishables (like crackers). Worth further exploration.
author: NA

description:
Dunkin' Donuts (1392 Lexington Ave)

Reliable source of high-fat, low nutrition calories.
author: NA

description:
Dunkin' Donuts (355 E 86th St #2)

Reliable source of high-fat, low nutrition calories.
author: NA

description:
Key Food (1769 2nd Ave, in Rupert Towers)

On our first foray, we found only some shrink-wrapped produce, plus local street people hanging out seemed hungry. If folks find more another time, please uplade this info.
author: NA

description:
Eli's Bread at The Vinegar Factory (431 E 91st Street)

Continuously throwing away recycling dumpsters full of bread every day.
author: NA

description:
Patak's

Gourmet deli on Madison Avenue between 89th and 90th Street. Location on map is approximate. Lots of black bags, but comparatively little good food. Some pre-made sandwiches and bread.
author: NA

description:
Gristede's (1343 Lexington Ave)

Dairy and eggs galore, a little not-so-great quality produce.
author: NA

description:
C-Town (1721 1st Ave)

Accessible supermarket food (produce, dairy, etc), athough on 1/2/12 we found very little that was useable.
author: NA

description:
Elm Health (1695 1st Ave)

Deserves more checking; let us know what you find. On a trailblaze in 2011 we found a huge amount of organic packaged goods - but we could have stumbled upon a once-a-quarter shelf emptying. When we came back in early 2012, there was loads of yogurt, including soy and almond milk varieties, but every container had had a hole cut in it and the bags were a complete mess.
author: NA

description:
Bagel Bob’s (1638 York Ave)

Like all Bagel Bob’s, no shortage of bagels of all varieties. Alex was thankful there were no onion bagels stinking up the bag.
author: NA

description:
Tal Bagels (333 E 86th St #1)

Here you will find…bagels!
author: NA

description:
Gristede's (350 E 86th St)

Usual supermarket assortment of average quality produce, packaged goods, dairy, baked goods. As of last check (January 2013) we found a lot of the usual supermarket finds.
author: NA

description:
Duane Reade (Northeast corner of 86th Street and 1st Ave)

At last check of this location (Jan 2013) we found a bunch of candy, pudding, babyfood and other odds and ends.
author: NA

description:
Eli's Food Market (1411 3rd Ave)

Most of their trash goes through a compressor, but on our first dive we found about five bags of uncompressed food including yogurt, almonds and butter.
author: NA

description:
Gristede's (1446 2nd Ave)

Huge piles of bags on blindingly lit stretch of 2nd Avenue - not for the shy. Similar to what's found at Gristede's in other parts of town, including produce, bread, dairy and more.
author: NA

description:
Food Emporium (1331 1st Ave)

We’ve checked this one twice recently (Nov 2010). First time, produce (some of which packaged), some past-date staples. It was on a high trolley that we unpacked and needed to re-pack. Second time, Cindy’s comments: "INSANE amounts of trash - 4 or 5 of those small dumpsters, all piled over head-high. Tons of bread, still frozen foods, sweets, produce, and more, and I only got through one or two dumpsters."
author: NA

description:
Grace's Marketplace (201 E 71st)

This is a large gourmet supermarket with wonderful and copious food thrown out. When the trailblaze team visited in September 2006, there were citrus fruits (grapefruit and oranges). A great deal of good corn on the cob, plenty of good bread and good bagels. And there were cute little pineapples, the size of a baseball.
author: NA

description:
Gourmet Garage (301 E 64th St)

At other locations in the city, this retailer has been locking its dumpsters or has “disappeared” them from the street. However, as of April 2010 we have reports that good food is accessible in the morning. A contributor writes: "I pass at 8:00am on weekdays. Two days in a row there has been a clear bag with rolls/bread, and varying packages of ready made salads (some with chicken added, etc). The expiration date is of the day before." This is a "mini" Gourmet Garbage; in several passes in 2012, Freegan.info members haven’t found anything in the evening, although morning may still be fine.
author: NA

description:
Morton Williams (917 9th Ave)

Produce, bagels, bread, sweets, packaged goods, clean packaged sandwiches. On the messy side, but on a pretty quiet street, so a good place for the shy. In October 2012 we found a bunch of produce and bread, some dairy products and a whole heap of cookies.
author: NA

description:
Dunkin' Donuts (815 10th Ave)

May vary. In October 2012, no donuts were out, but there was a lot of pumpkin donut mix.
author: NA

description:
Gristede's (8th Avenue and 54th Street)

Lots  of produce, bread, eggs, and packaged goods here. In the past employees got a bit angry with us, but didn’t try to stop us. (Updated October 2012)
author: NA

description:
Bagel Stix (891 8th Ave)

Bagels plus breakfasty muffins.
author: NA

description:
Food Emporium (810 8th Ave)

Loads of stuff. We found veggies, tofu, bread, dairy, nuts and seeds. It’s a bit overwhelming here, as there is a lot of stuff. (Updated January 2010)
author: NA

description:
Dunkin' Donuts (693 9th Ave #1)

Typical DD fare! (Updated January 2010)
author: NA

description:
Hale & Hearty Soups (49 W 42nd St)

Bread, salads.
author: NA

description:
Pret à Manger (11 W 42nd St)

Loaves of bread and organic packaged salads and sandwiches. As of September 2009, a former employee says they donate all their leftovers. Experienced divers know many stores make this claim; however, the pickings have been slim for a while.
author: NA

description:
Pret à Manger (135 W 50th St)

Loaves of bread and organic packaged salads and sandwiches.
author: NA

description:
Pax Wholesome Foods (225 W 42nd St)

Wrap sandwiches, pizza, baked goods. Fairly narrow time window‚ stuff goes out late and is picked up by 1:30 AM or so.
author: NA

description:
Pax Wholesome Foods (80 W 40th St #1)

Bagels, rolls, variety of other stuff. Less consistent than other Pax stores.
author: NA

description:
Pax Wholesome Foods (1350 Broadway)

LOTS of really expensive sandwiches, especially wraps. Muffins, bagels. Very popular, so sometimes stuff is gone by the time you get there.
author: NA

description:
Hale & Hearty Soup (462 7th Avenue)

Entire bag of cut romaine lettuce, prepacked mixed salads in plastic sealed bowls. Soup veggies and beans sometimes.
author: NA

description:
D’Agostino (1031 1st Ave)

Bread and good produce in large quantities. In 2011/12 we found plenty of produce plus pies, eggs, soy protein things. Previous finds include fancy items like organic drink mix and olive oil. There are regular neighborhood divers so please share.
author: NA

description:
Dunkin' Donuts (1024 1st Ave)

The normal DD stuff. Bags are put out on 1st Ave side by the city trash can.
author: NA

description:
Così (60 E 56th St)

We found focaccia bread and fresh unbaked dough, but kind of a “2nd choice” location.
author: NA

description:
Tal Bagels (977 1st Ave)

Very fresh bagels, not mixed with trash.
author: NA

description:
D’Agostino (966 1st Ave)

Massive amounts of produce in a several mini-dumpsters on the sidewalk.
author: NA

description:
Food Emporium (969 2nd Ave)

We haven’t been there yet – probably fine!
author: NA

description:
Pain Quotidien (937 2nd Ave)

Huge rounds of crusty whole grain sourdough bread that stay moist inside for many days after being tossed. Even on days when the whole loaves aren’t there, you’ll find quarter and half loaves and/or sliced bread. Also some baguettes, croissants, muffins. See their store listings and let us know what you find at other locations.
author: NA

description:
Café Europa

Pizza, salads, sandwiches. Note: No such business could be found on "42nd Street between 5th and Madison", so maybe refers instead to one of the other cafés on the block?
author: NA

description:
The Bread Factory Cafe (935 8th Ave)

Bagels galore...
author: NA

description:
The Bread Factory Cafe (600 9th Ave)

Pies (big ones) and pizza slices, unwrapped, messy.
author: NA

description:
International Grocery (543 9th Ave)

Worth checking if you're blowing through the Port Authority bus terminal. We found Kabul brand flatbread and some produce, but not a lot. We didn’t find anything of note here on a Monday night in January 2010.
author: NA

description:
Stiles Farmers Market (352 W 52nd St)

This is a semi-open-air produce market. The night we went their dumpster didn't yield a lot of usable produce, but if you're in the area it's worth a look. (Updated January 2010)
author: NA

description:
D'Agostino's (578 3rd Ave)

Trash right outside the stores. Lots of produce, much of it very high quality; puts out lots of excellent bread. Tends to have a very short window between putting out and having their private trash carrier pick up; arrive by 9pm for best results. As of late 2011 this area became something of a “dumpster desert”, with both D’Ag supermarkets switching to putting trash out in the morning.
author: NA

description:
Gristede's (460 3rd Ave)

Quite a lot of packaged, precooked food, including deli cheeses and meats, in a series of trash cans on the 32nd Street side. Easy location to sort through without being harassed. Well known to neighborhood regulars. Started locking up trash in the spring of 2011.
author: NA

description:
Zaro's Bread Basket (Grand Central Terminal)

Location on map approximate (originally noted to be at "370 Lexington Ave"). Friday evenings starting at 6:30 or so, bags and bags and BAGS of bread and bagels are put out. In addition, more bags of raw bread/bagel dough (shaped and portioned already) are also put out... take it home, pop it in the oven for 10-15 minutes at 350 degrees, and voila - freshly baked breads (and really good!!). Doesn't get much more freshly made than that. Haven't tried other days and times - honestly, we get enough on one visit on Fridays that there's no need to go back. And we take maybe 1/20th of what's there, so there's plenty to go around.
author: NA

description:
Le Pain Quotidien (70 W 40th St)

Throws out even on Saturdays (and also Sundays), starting early, around 7:00 or 7:30, with the usual delectable pastries and huge breads and good breadsticks and sliced bread too…. abundant!
author: NA

description:
Daniel’s Bagels (569 3rd Ave)

What else? Bagels!
author: NA

description:
Dunkin' Donuts (567 3rd Ave)

Enuff donuts to stuff a kop, plus they have…bagels!
author: NA

description:
Guy and Gallard (339 7th Ave)

Dumpster is on 29th Street side. Bagels, bread, salads, fruit salads, sandwiches, prepared gourmet meal thingees, fresh squeezed juice, yogurt and granola, etc. Kind of have to really reach in the bags to find good stuff sometimes, but there's lots of it.
author: NA

description:
CVS & Starbucks (750 6th Ave)

Both stores throw out massive bags of sandwiches and salads, about 1x per week. (Updated October 2011)
author: NA

description:
Gristede's (307 W 26th St)

Recessed dumpster is on 26th between 8th and 9th Avenues. A New York City megawaster is up to its usual tricks in Chelsea. The usual assortment of produce, dairy and eggs, bread and prepared foods. On the night freegan.info scouted, location had usable food but the dumpster was in messy condition.
author: NA

description:
Gristede's (225 9th Ave)

A worker said we "couldn't go through the garbage", but we did anyway and found produce and boxes of cereal.
author: NA

description:
Gristede's (221 8th Ave)

The "Megastore". On the night freegan.info scouted, location had usable food, although the dumpster was in messy condition.
author: NA

description:
Murray's Bagels (249 8th Ave)

Clean bagels, no muss no fuss.
author: NA

description:
Garden of Eden (162 W 23rd St)

Yupscale NYC based chain that specializes in produce, prepared foods and luxury products.
author: NA

description:
Duane Reade (131 8th Ave)

This new store was reported to us in March 2010 as having “TONS of fabulous food… Gourmet salads, breads, sandwiches and much much more. It’s all packaged, sealed and with today’s expiration date. It’s a brand new store that few people know about yet so there’s a TON of food to go around.” We were there in August 2011 and yes, there was some stuff but don’t expect miracles.
author: NA

description:
Le Pain Quotidien (124 7th Ave)

Huge rounds of crusty whole grain sourdough bread that stay moist inside for many days after being tossed. Even on days when the whole loaves aren’t there, you’ll find quarter and half loaves. Also some baguettes, croissants, muffins. Sometimes the stuff at these stores is in bags that had been held for City Harvest - folks there confirm that if their bags are on the sidewalk with the trash, which they shouldn’t be of course, then City Harvest is definitely NOT picking up the food.
author: NA

description:
Le Pain Quotidien (52 9th Ave)

Huge rounds of crusty whole grain sourdough bread that stay moist inside for many days after being tossed. Even on days when the whole loaves aren’t there, you’ll find quarter and half loaves. Also some baguettes, croissants, muffins. In July 2011, I found what looked like an unbaked round but turned out to be an entire chocolate mousse cake. Sometimes the stuff at these stores is in bags that had been held for City Harvest - folks there confirm that if their bags are on the sidewalk with the trash, which they shouldn’t be of course, then City Harvest is definitely NOT picking up the food.
author: NA

description:
Manhattan Fruit Exchange (448 W 16th St)

Not for the shy, or for big groups. You need to climb onto the loading dock and root through big dumpsters, but the quantity and quality at this wholesaler make it worthwhile. Workers there are pretty friendly and tolerant, but huge trucks are coming in and out; if you are in the way you will  be asked to leave.
author: NA

description:
Western Beef (431 W 16th St)

A reader wrote us, “I got 6 bags of perfectly good rotisserie chicken and friend chicken in the trash.” We were there in August 2011 and found some stuff, mainly dairy and veggies. Messy, in mid-size dumpsters.
author: NA

description:
Associated Supermarket (255 W 14th St)

Produce and more.
author: NA

description:
Zaro's Bakery (920 Broadway)

EDIT: PERMANENTLY CLOSED

Dumpsters are on the south side of 21st St just east of Broadway. Tip came in from a worker there: "Every night, a huge load of bread and pastries from that morning are discarded. Last night, I put out two bags of bread so heavy I could hardly lift them. I try to put the bags of clean food on the right or left side of the dumpsters rather than IN them." It's worth checking other Zaro's locations as well, including Penn Station and Grand Central.
author: NA

description:
Morton Williams Supermarket (278 Park Ave)

Mainly produce.
author: NA

description:
Natural Green Market (162 3rd Ave)

Health food store. Closes at 10:30pm, collects after 12:30am.
author: NA

description: Gramercy Bagel (246 3rd Ave)
author: NA

description: David's Bagels (273 1st Ave)
author: NA

description:
Whole Foods (4 Union Square E #4)

Dumpsters are in the back of store on the north side of 13th St between University and Broadway. A sneaky one and has sometimes been hostile to dumpster divers. In the post-Occupy era, the compost has been moved much deeper into the indoor loading bays, so much harder to get to without being noticed or confronted.  Their stuff is in compost-type bins. Mainly it’s fruits and vegetables, sometimes in remarkable quantity and excellent condition; they also dump flowers and bread in these bins.
author: NA

description:
Trader Joe's (142 E 14th St)

A very clandestine waster, you need to be discrete and fast to get this one. They put stuff out on rolling carts all day long, in front of their loading bay closer to 3rd Ave but also in front of their liquor outlet further west. If you're there more than 5 minutes they send some poor employee out to say "I'm moving this cart indoors". One employee says to come at exactly 10pm, everyone's too busy with closing to worry about moving the garbage back indoors. So why bother? Because when it's good it's really good -- think mountains of citrus, nut butters, tofu products, cookies and cereals in perfect condition, cases of prepared foods with one container damaged; one time a 10-pound bar of dark chocolate in pristine condition. Some divers advocate a "grab-n-go" approach to the bags -- anything heavy is worth taking to sort thru elsewhere.
author: NA

description:
Garden of Eden (7 E 14th St)

What a mess, all piled into mini-dumpsters. In addition to their bags, in the dumpsters and outside when they overflow, sometimes yielding raw meat and fish (think pet food!), check the large rolling garbage containers, which hold all the deli hot food (a specialty of this chain; may contain cooked chickens) as well as salad bar and other produce.
author: NA

description:
Petco (860 Broadway)

Lots of companion animal food.

Keep in mind that carnivorous companions generally love the meat and fish "unfit for human consumption" that all the supermarkets throw out. With a little care, don't take animal products that are not quite cold or quite hot; wash everything in cold water and wrap in clean packaging; freeze what you can't use right way; always cook before you serve it and your companions need never eat overprocessed byproduct kibble again.
author: NA

description:
Bagels & More (200 W 14th St)

Original source referred to the "Bagelry (14th Street and 7th Ave)" but no such store could be found. Bagels & More marked instead pending verification. Puts out more bagels than Bagel Bob's, and sometimes Krispy Kreme donuts or salads as well.
author: NA

description:
LifeThyme Natural Market (410 6th Ave)

Large health food store. Closes at 10pm. Not the most wasteful in the neighborhood, but still, they toss some decent stuff. Their black bags sometimes yield packs of nuts, vegan baked goods, dried fruit, small amounts of produce, lots of patches of cut live wheatgrass. For the intrepid, dig into the hot food bags - they empty loads of cooked organic food every night, all mixed together in big messy bags. They used to let folks take the hot food before they dumped it, but no more, sad to say.
author: NA

description:
Citarella (424 6th Ave)

Conspicuous upscale market For years it was impossible to find the trash. Lately (spring 2012) they’re putting out mountains of plastic bags, like their less chichi competitors. Found gorgeous greens, clean and in bags by themselves, plus assorted produce in mixed mess. There were also lots of stripped fish carcasses - stew for the intrepid pescovore.
author: NA

description:
Gristede's (3 Sheridan Square)
The trash is around the corner from the market itself, next to a parking garage, across from One if By Land (fancy restaurant) and west of the trash for the apartment building. Lotsa stuff, not often seriously dived.
author: NA

description:
Le Pain Quotidien (10 5th Ave)

Huge rounds of crusty whole grain sourdough bread, stays moist inside for many days after being tossed. Even on days when the whole loaves aren’t there, you’ll find quarter and half loaves. Also some baguettes and occasionally sweets - muffins, croissants, scones, pain chocolat.
author: NA

description:
Integral Yoga Natural Foods (229 W 13th St)

Small health food store; no produce.
author: NA

description:
Peanut Butter and Co. (240 Sullivan St)

Peanut butter and banana sandwiches, whole grain bread, celery and carrot sticks, cups of peanut butter.
author: NA

description: Produce market (large, I forget the name) at Carmine and Varick Streets (location on map is approximate). Several cartons of very good produce.
author: NA

description:
Bagel Bob's (51 University Pl)

An East Village freegan legend; out of the many bags of plain old trash, feel for the one to three bags that contains obvious bagel and bialy shapes. Huge bags of bagels, mini bagels, bagel bits (sort of like Munchkins, but bagels), cinnamon buns, struedels, and bialys not intermingled with other food and garbage. Very popular. Don't bother on Mondays.
author: NA

description:
Gristede's (25 University Pl)
TONS of eggs, cheese, packaged goods, bread and some produce. They throw out lots of food regularly, really worth a look.
author: NA

description:
Au Bon Pain (58 E 8th St)

Bread and pastry chain. This one tosses lots of pastries when it closes around 11:30 pm. Also, bagels, rolls, breadsticks, etc.
author: NA

description:
Gristede's (246 Mercer St)

Lots of fruit and other produce. Bread, hummus, other packaged foods.
author: NA

description:
Le Pain Quotidien (65 Bleecker St)

Huge rounds of crusty whole grain sourdough bread that stay moist inside for many days after being tossed. Even on days when the whole loaves aren’t there, you’ll find quarter and half loaves and/or sliced bread. Also some baguettes, croissants, muffins. See their store listings and let us know what you find at other locations.
author: NA

description:
Dunkin' Donuts (1225 1st Ave)

Not a particularly fruitful location of this serial waster.
author: NA

description:
Commodities Natural Market (165 1st Ave)

This health food store has had small but good finds recently (January 2013), including produce, juice, and packaged vegan salads.
author: NA

De Robertis Pasticceria & Caffe (176 1st Ave)

description:
Whole Foods (95 E Houston St)

You can find many vegetables and fruits. The dumpsters are just around the corner at Chrystie St. They take out the trash at around 16:00 every day. The employees are very friendly and would not disturb you as you find your treasures.

NOTE: As of 2011-2012, everything has been behind closed doors, which was not the case in the past. If you find this changes, write it here.
author: NA

description:
Finest Produce Corporation (119 Chrystie St)

This is a wholesaler. Dumpster with bulk produce; sometimes quite a lot, sometimes very little in good shape.
author: NA

description:
Food Emporium (316 Greenwich St)

Lots of produce, meat, prepared foods, and all manner of other items in chest-high dumpsters in front of the store. Very exposed location, super wide sidewalk. Confirmed 3/5/2012.
author: NA

description:
Wichcraft (397 Greenwich St)

At the end of the night, the restaurant Wichcraft throws away between 10-20 sandwiches which were made earlier in the day. They are all cold sandwiches (goat cheese, chicken salad, chickpea, tuna) and can be eaten or stored for a few days. If you go after closing (around 8:30pm on weekdays and 5:30pm on weekends) they will probably happily give you a bag of sandwiches. There are 10 others around the city. Confirmed 3/5/2012.
author: NA

description:
Le Pain Quotidien (81 W Broadway)

Huge rounds of crusty whole grain sourdough bread that stay moist inside for many days after being tossed. Even on days when the whole loaves aren’t there, you’ll find quarter and half loaves and/or sliced bread. Also some baguettes, croissants, muffins.
author: NA

description:
Whole Foods (270 Greenwhich St)

We’ve only tried there once (3/5/2012) but didn’t find anything. If you find the secret, share it here!

description:
Little Pie Company (424 West 43d St)

We found... little pies! Lots of them. Mostly meaty or eggy, like pot pies and quiche, all in perfect condition and individually shrink-wrapped. Locals were happy to take them. Also raw pie dough and flour, unpackaged, a bit messy but worthwhile for the adventurous freegan chef.
author: NA

description:
Chelsea Piers

On the west side of the highway at 20th St, there are a lot of TV and film productions at the Silver Screen Studios building, which means a lot of catered food thrown out.  Some other stuff, too. Come late at night and look for the dumpsters facing the bike path. Location on map is approximate.
author: NA

description:
Gourmet Garage (117 7th Ave S)

Perhaps the neighbors complained, because the dumpsters that used to sit outside this yuppie store are no longer there. If you notice the situation change, update this description!
author: NA

description:

Decadent desserts.
author: NA

description:
Vosges Haut-Chocolat (132 Spring St)

Throws out sample truffles. Usually only around 5-10 a night, but still really fancy tasty goods. Trash is out around 8:30pm, pickup is early but usually not before 9pm.
author: NA

description:
Khim's Millenium Market (260 Bushwick Ave)

Puts their stuff in a few bags on the curb next to a compost bin.You can almost always count on some good packaged food and a little produce. Every night except Saturday after around 9pm. Picked up after midnight.
author: mojoy

description:
Khim's Millenium Market (294 Graham Ave)

A little Khim's with a compost bin for produce. Haven't seen the garbage put out yet, but I'm sure if you see bags, there's something good in them. Please update with times if you find something.
author: Andrea

description:
Khim's Millenium Market (265 Bedford Ave)

One of the most popular salvaging sites, it is highly probable someone else will check this dumpster before or after you, so please, keep it neat and DON'T TEAR OPEN BAGS! The dumpster is tucked inside a gap in the fence, sometimes it's outside when there's cardboard put out. You will almost always find something amazing here! It's unbelievable what they throw out. I've found 40 jars of organic peanut butter, cases of chocolate, juice, Cliff Bars, avocados, cookies, honey, you name it! Especially likely are those vegan macrobiotic prepared meals and sandwiches. They put stuff out after 9pm and it doesn't get picked up until like 5am, so take your time and don't leave a mess. The "landlord" lives above the store and he can be a jerk so just ignore him.
author: mojoy

description:
Key Food (575 Grand Street)

This Key Food has a lot of organic stuff, so it's worth checking out. Dumpsters are in the parking lot, but sometimes the gates are closed later at night. I've found lots of great stuff here, even Hoegarden beer!
author: mojoy

description:
Mr. Kiwi's (957 Broadway)

This place is a haven of organic goodness in the middle of an otherwise deprived neighborhood. Please support Mr. Kiwi with your dollars and foodstamps! Haven't seen their trash put out yet, but I'm sure once it's found, it will yield some treasures.
author: mojoy

description:
Brooklyn's Natural (49 Bogart St)

Not sure of the schedule yet, but worth taking a look whenever you pass by at night. There will be a row of small dumpsters here along Seigel St.
author: mojoy

description:
Damascus Bakery (56 Gold St)

I haven't been here too often but the times I have I've found a lot of pita bread, some in trash bags and others in the kind of bags you'll see on a supermarket shelf. The dumpsters are in a fenced pen that's unlocked, just open the door and walk in.
author: Andrea

description: Food Emporium, 1066 3rd Avenue, New York, NY
